 496: 


 497: 


 498: # -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


 499: 


 500: cdef class FrameR:


 501:     """


 502:     FrameR is really an iterator class,


 503:     to be able to iterate through matrices. FrameR


 504:     keeps a connection to its source SdifFile but all


 505:     managing and indexing is done by the SdifFile, to


 506:     keep things central. In particular, the matrices


 507:     resulting from calling its 'next()' method (or iterating


 508:     with 'for') have no connection to the FrameR and talk


 509:     directly to the SdifFile, which, eventually, updates


 510:     the FrameR if needed.


 511:     It is only used for reading and, in particular, one


 512:     would never create a FrameR but receive it as result of


 513:     iterating through a SdifFile


 514:     """


 515:     cdef SdifFrameHeaderT *header


 516:     cdef SdifFile source


 517:     cdef SdifFileT *source_this


 518:

 662: cdef class SdifFile:


/* "pysdif/_pysdif.pyx":662
 * # -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 * 
 * cdef class SdifFile:             # <<<<<<<<<<<<<<
 *     """
 *     SdifFile(filename, mode="r")
 */

struct __pyx_vtabstruct_6pysdif_7_pysdif_SdifFile {
  void (*init_read)(struct __pyx_obj_6pysdif_7_pysdif_SdifFile *);
  void (*init_containers)(struct __pyx_obj_6pysdif_7_pysdif_SdifFile *);
  void (*init_write)(struct __pyx_obj_6pysdif_7_pysdif_SdifFile *);
  void (*finalize_frame)(struct __pyx_obj_6pysdif_7_pysdif_SdifFile *);
  void (*read_signature)(struct __pyx_obj_6pysdif_7_pysdif_SdifFile *);
  void (*read_matrix_data)(struct __pyx_obj_6pysdif_7_pysdif_SdifFile *);
  void (*reinit)(struct __pyx_obj_6pysdif_7_pysdif_SdifFile *);
};

 663:     """


 664:     SdifFile(filename, mode="r")


 665: 


 666:     mode is "r":read | "w": write | "wr" or "rw":read-write


 667: 


 668:     this is the low level interface for reading and writing sdif files


 669:     it mirrors the sdif library quite transparently so that the example files


 670:     and utilities using it can be directly translated with it. in particular


 671:     it does not create any intermediate objects, even the data of the matrices


 672:     is a numpy array mapped to the c array read from disk, so no allocation takes


 673:     place.


 674: 


 675:     to read for ex. 1TRC format:


 676: 


 677:     sdif_file = SdifFile('filename.sdif')


 678:     sig1TRC = str2signature("1TRC")


 679:     while not sdif_file.eof:


 680:         sdif_file.read_frame_header()


 681:         if sdif_file.frame_numerical_signature) == sig1TRC:


 682:             print sdif_file.time


 683:             for n in range(sdif_file.matrices_in_frame):


 684:                 sdif_file.read_matrix_header()


 685:                 if sdif_file.matrix_numerical_signature == sig1TRC:


 686:                     data = sdif_file.get_matrix_data()


 687:                     # data is now a numpy array but you must copy the data if


 688:                     # you intend to keep it after you have read the matrix.


 689:                     # One you read a new matrix, this data will be no longer valid


 690:                     print data


 691: 


 692:     a more natural way:


 693: 


 694:     sdif_file = SdifFile('filename.sdif')


 695:     for frame in sdif_file:


 696:         if frame.signature == "1TRC":


 697:             print frame.time


 698:             for matrix in frame:


 699:                 if matrix.signature == "1TRC":


 700:                     print matrix.get_data()


 701: 


 702:     the frames and the matrices resulting from the iteration


 703:     are only guaranteed to be valid as long as no new frames and matrices are read


 704: 


 705:     to write a SdifFile:


 706: 


 707:     f = SdifFile('new_sdif.sdif', 'w')


 708:     # these are optional


 709:     f.add_NVT({


 710:         'name' : 'my name',


 711:         'date' : time.asctime(time.localtime())


 712:     })


 713:     f.add_frame_type('1NEW', '1ABC NewMatrix, 1FQ0 New1FQ0')


 714:     f.add_matrix_type('1ABC', 'Column1, Column2')


 715:     # now you can begin adding frames


 716:     frame = f.new_frame('1NEW', time_now)


 717:     frame.add_matrix('1ABC', array([


 718:         [0,     1.2],


 719:         [3.5,   8.13],


 720:         ...


 721:         ]))


 722:     frame.write()


 723: 


 724:     # say we just want to take the data from an existing


 725:     # sdiffile, modify it and write it back


 726:     in_sdif = SdifFile("existing-file.sdif")


 727:     out_sdif = SdifFile("outfile.sdif", "w")


 728:     out_sdif.clone_definitions(in_sdif)


 729:     for in_frame in in_sdif:


 730:         if in_frame.signature == "1NEW":


 731:             new_frame = out_sdif.new_frame("1NEW", in_frame.time)


 732:             in_data = in_frame.get_matrix_data() # we know there is only one matrix


 733:             # multiply the second column by 0.5


 734:             in_data[:,1] *= 0.5


 735:             new_frame.add_matrix('1ABC', in_data)


 736:             new_frame.write()


 737:     """


 738: 


 739:     cdef SdifFileT *this


 740:     cdef readonly int eof
